---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "@/components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";

const navLinks = [
  { href: "/", label: "Phidea" },
  { href: "/#archive", label: "Topics" },
  { href: "/#subscribe", label: "Subscribe" },
];
const navCta = { href: "#subscribe", label: "Subscribe →" };
---

<Layout variant="ai-visibility">
  <Nav variant="ai-visibility" links={navLinks} cta={navCta} />

  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-head">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>Topic 01 · Distribution</span>
          <span>April 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>When a carrier isn't cited by ChatGPT.</h1>
        <p class="standfirst">
          Your Google rank and your ChatGPT citation rate live on different systems. One of them is about to matter a lot more.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="article-body">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <p>
          Run twelve common insurance buyer questions into ChatGPT. "What's the cheapest auto insurance in my state." "Am I covered if I hit a deer." "Which insurance is best for a new driver." Whatever fits your market. See who gets cited.
        </p>

        <p>
          Most carriers who run this for the first time get an unpleasant surprise. Their own brand comes up less often than expected. A competitor they wouldn't have considered a peer comes up more. The result is usually consistent across the four big assistants, not random.
        </p>

        <p>
          The reason is mechanical. A search engine gives you a ranked list of links. An assistant gives you a sentence, composed by the model from whatever it has read. What it has read is a moving mix of two-year-old training data and whatever the web search picks up when you type your question.
        </p>

        <p>
          None of that looks much like your SEO funnel.
        </p>

        <p>
          The pattern we keep seeing across a handful of markets: the carriers cited most often aren't the ones with the biggest brand. They're the ones mentioned most in third-party coverage. NerdWallet. The Zebra. MoneyGeek. Insurance Business. Those sites are training data now. Your product microsite, in most cases, is not.
        </p>

        <p>
          So what do you actually do about it. Five things, and none of them ship by Friday.
        </p>

        <p>
          One, check your <code>robots.txt</code>. GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot, and Google-Extended all respect it. Plenty of carriers are blocking at least one. Usually the reason is lost to institutional memory. Fixing it is a one-line change and then an afternoon of waiting for the crawlers to notice.
        </p>

        <p>
          Two, rewrite your product pages in question-and-answer shape. FAQ format gets cited more reliably than prose product descriptions. This is not a keyword thing. The assistants prefer the shape that already looks like a question and an answer.
        </p>

        <p>
          Three, treat the assistants as four different products. Claude refuses to quote specific prices. ChatGPT and Gemini will. Perplexity cites whoever has the cleanest structured data on the open web, which is usually an affiliate comparison site, not you. If you want to win on all four, you're running four different plays.
        </p>

        <p>
          Four, measure it. Run the same forty real buyer queries on each assistant. Note who gets cited. Compare with your actual market share. The gap is your AI distribution problem. It's a different number from your SEO one, and for most carriers it's bigger.
        </p>

        <p>
          Five, the part no one wants to hear: your policy wording itself matters now. When a buyer asks "am I covered for flooding" the model doesn't copy your policy. It composes a new sentence from it. If your text is ambiguous the model fills the gap with something that sounds reassuring and isn't true. You can't hide your policy from the crawlers. You have to write it so that when it gets paraphrased into something new, the something new is still correct. That's a harder fix than anything else on this list.
        </p>

        <p>
          Anyway, that's where things stand in April. Next week: what happens the morning after OpenAI ships a silent model update, and why a carrier's refusal rate on coverage questions can move twenty-two percent without anyone pushing a button.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="subscribe" class="subscribe-strip">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="section-label">Phidea Weekly</div>
        <h3>Keep reading.</h3>
        <p>
          One short piece per week on AI in insurance: what regulators are actually doing, what the model providers are actually shipping, what carriers are actually trying.
        </p>
        <form action="https://buttondown.email/api/emails/embed-subscribe/phidea" method="POST" class="signup">
          <input type="hidden" name="tag" value="ai-visibility" />
          <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Your email" required />
          <button type="submit">Subscribe →</button>
        </form>
        <p class="signup-small">One email per week. Unsubscribe in one click.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .wrap-article { max-width: 680px; padding-left: 24px; padding-right: 24px; margin: 0 auto; }

  .article-head { padding: 72px 0 32px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); }
  .article-meta {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .article-head h1 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 44px;
    line-height: 1.12;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: 20px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .article-body { padding: 48px 0 64px; }
  .article-body p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.72;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .article-body p code {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: var(--soft);
    padding: 1px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .section-label {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .subscribe-strip {
    padding: 72px 0;
    background: var(--soft);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .subscribe-strip h3 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 28px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .subscribe-strip p {
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup { display: flex; gap: 10px; max-width: 520px; }
  .signup input[type=email] {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 14px 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
    background: var(--bg);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .signup button {
    padding: 14px 24px;
    border: none;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--bg);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-weight: 500;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup button:hover { background: var(--accent); }
  .signup-small {
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-top: 12px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .article-head h1 { font-size: 30px; }
    .standfirst { font-size: 17px; }
    .article-body p { font-size: 17px; }
    .signup { flex-direction: column; }
  }
</style>
